eyPoints":["Four-marker test detects 90%+ of early-stage pancreatic cancers","Research-stage only—no clinical use yet, no regulatory approval","Early detection matters, but survival gains still unproven"],"source":{"name":"ScienceDaily Health","url":"https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2026/03/260323005540.htm"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/pancreatic-cancer-blood-test-real-progress-with-re/main.jpg","alt":"Pancreatic cancer blood test: real progress with real limits"},"subtitle":"Razina dokaza: istraživački stadij s jasnim ograničenjima","subtitleEn":"A study with rare promise—and the usual caveats","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/pancreatic-cancer-blood-test-real-progress-with-re/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A study with rare promise—and the usual caveats"},"tags":["Pancreatic Cancer","Early Detection","Clinical Trial"],"geo":{"name":"Global","lat":0,"lon":0,"countryCode":"XX"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$6"},{"id":"2026-03-23-gut-bacteria-and-diet-a-10-000-person-study-with-l","dbId":627,"title":"Gut bacteria and diet: A 10,000-person study with limits","titleEn":"Gut bacteria and diet: A 10,000-person study with limits","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"A decade into the microbiome boom, the promise of tailoring diets to gut bacteria remains more research aspiration than clinical reality.","execSummary":"This large-scale observational study (10,068 participants) maps persistent food-microbiome links, suggesting potential for personalized nutrition—but remains at the research stage. The angle focuses on what the evidence *actually* shows (correlations, not causation) and why patients shouldn’t expect clinical changes yet, while highlighting the study’s methodological limits and next steps for validation.","keyPoints":["Food–microbiome links persist across 10,000 individuals","Personalized diet simulations—still research-stage only","No direct patient impact yet, but a step toward precision nutrition"],"source":{"name":"Nature Medicine","url":"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41591-026-04312-x"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/gut-bacteria-and-diet-a-10-000-person-study-with-l/main.jpg","alt":"Gut bacteria and diet: A 10,000-person study with limits"},"subtitle":"Velika studija pokazuje trajne obrasce – ali ključna pitanja ostaju","subtitleEn":"Observational data, not a prescription—what this study actually shows","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/gut-bacteria-and-diet-a-10-000-person-study-with-l/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Observational data, not a prescription—what this study actually shows"},"tags":["Microbiome","Nutrition","Public Health"],"geo":{"name":"Menlo Park, CA","lat":37.4529,"lon":-122.1817,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$7","part1En":"$8","part2En":"$9"},{"id":"2026-03-23-ozempics-mental-health-perks-real-or-research-mira","dbId":623,"title":"Ozempic’s mental health perks: real or research mirage?","titleEn":"Ozempic’s mental health perks: real or research mirage?","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"When semaglutide (Ozempic) first surged in popularity for weight loss, its mental health effects were an afterthought.","execSummary":"A large observational study links Ozempic to reduced depression, anxiety, and addiction rates—but the mechanism remains unclear. This analysis dissects the evidence level, clinical irrelevance for current patients, and why regulatory bodies aren’t acting yet, framing it as a research signal rather than a therapeutic breakthrough.","keyPoints":["Ozempic users show 30% fewer psychiatric hospital visits","Substance use disorders dropped—but mechanisms unclear","Lifestyle vs. biology: study can’t separate the two"],"source":{"name":"ScienceDaily Health","url":"https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2026/03/260322020250.htm"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/ozempics-mental-health-perks-real-or-research-mira/main.jpg","alt":"Ozempic’s mental health perks: real or research mirage?"},"subtitle":"Velika studija otkriva neočekivane benefite, ali ostaju ključna pitanja o uzrocima i dugoročnim učincima","subtitleEn":"A large observational study hints at mental health benefits—but the evidence isn’t clinical-grade yet.","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/ozempics-mental-health-perks-real-or-research-mira/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A large observational study hints at mental health benefits—but the evidence isn’t clinical-grade yet."},"tags":["Ozempic","Mental Health","Clinical Trial"],"geo":{"name":"Global","lat":0,"lon":0,"countryCode":"XX"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$a","part1En":"$b","part2En":"$c"},{"id":"2026-03-23-a-brainstem-link-to-hypertensionwhat-the-evidence-","dbId":621,"title":"A brainstem link to hypertension—what the evidence really shows","titleEn":"A brainstem link to hypertension—what the evidence really shows","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"High blood pressure affects [1.","execSummary":"This study identifies a brainstem region linking breathing control to blood pressure regulation, offering a new mechanistic insight into hypertension—but remains far from clinical application. The angle focuses on separating proven findings (neural pathway) from unanswered questions (therapeutic potential, safety, human trials).","keyPoints":["Brainstem region tied to breathing also raises blood pressure","Deactivating it normalized BP in lab experiments","No direct patient impact yet—early-stage research"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/a-brainstem-link-to-hypertensionwhat-the-evidence-/main.jpg","alt":"A brainstem link to hypertension—what the evidence really shows"},"subtitle":"Što studija stvarno pokazuje – i što još uvijek ne znamo","subtitleEn":"The study’s limits are as important as its findings","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/a-brainstem-link-to-hypertensionwhat-the-evidence-/subtitle.jpg","alt":"The study’s limits are as important as its findings"},"tags":["Hypertension","Brain Research","Neurology"],"geo":{"name":"Hrvatska (Croatia)","lat":45.1,"lon":15.2,"countryCode":"HR"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$d","part1En":"$e","part2En":"$f"},{"id":"2026-03-23-novartis-bets-3b-on-a-pi3k-inhibitorbut-how-solid-","dbId":617,"title":"Novartis Bets $3B on a PI3Kα Inhibitor—But How Solid Is the Evidence?","titleEn":"Novartis Bets $3B on a PI3Kα Inhibitor—But How Solid Is the Evidence?","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"Novartis’ $3 billion acquisition of [Pikavation](https://www.","execSummary":"Novartis's $3B acquisition of Pikavation centers on SNV4818, an early-stage PI3Kα inhibitor for HR+/HER2- metastatic breast cancer. This analysis dissects the **evidence gap** between preliminary promise and clinical reality, emphasizing what the data *don’t* yet show for patients today. The move underscores industry trends in precision oncology but serves as a case study in how early-phase trials must be contextualized—lest hope outpace science.","keyPoints":["Novartis acquires Pikavation for up to $3B","Lead drug SNV4818 in early trials for HR+/HER2- breast cancer","No proof yet it outperforms existing PI3Kα therapies"],"source":{"name":"GEN News","url":"https://www.genengnews.com/topics/cancer/novartis-acquires-pikavation-for-up-to-3b-expanding-cancer-pipeline/"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/novartis-bets-3b-on-a-pi3k-inhibitorbut-how-solid-/main.jpg","alt":"Novartis Bets $3B on a PI3Kα Inhibitor—But How Solid Is the Evidence?"},"subtitle":"Rana klinička ispitivanja, bez regulacijskog odobrenja","subtitleEn":"A high-stakes gamble on a pan-mutant inhibitor—with Phase 1 data as the only hand shown so far.","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/novartis-bets-3b-on-a-pi3k-inhibitorbut-how-solid-/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A high-stakes gamble on a pan-mutant inhibitor—with Phase 1 data as the only hand shown so far."},"tags":["Novartis","Oncology","Pikavation","SNV4818","Clinical Trials"],"geo":{"name":"Basel, Switzerland","lat":47.5577,"lon":7.5733,"countryCode":"XX"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$10","part1En":"$11","part2En":"$12"},{"id":"2026-03-23-mrna-cancer-vaccines-what-we-know-what-we-don-t","dbId":615,"title":"mRNA Cancer Vaccines: What We Know, What We Don't","titleEn":"mRNA Cancer Vaccines: What We Know, What We Don't","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"The race toward mRNA cancer vaccines is accelerating, with scientists reporting rapid progress on treatments designed to help the immune system recognize and destroy tumors.","execSummary":"This article dissects the *actual* evidence behind mRNA cancer vaccines—separating confirmed lab progress from clinical reality. It highlights the gap between early-phase trials and patient accessibility, while addressing how misinformation risks distorting public perception of a technology that, despite promise, remains years from widespread use.","keyPoints":["mRNA cancer vaccines advance in research","Misinformation complicates public understanding","Timeline for clinical use remains unclear"],"source":{"name":"MedicalXpress","url":"https://medicalxpress.com/news/2026-03-cancer-vaccines-treatment-misinformation-mrna.html"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/mrna-cancer-vaccines-what-we-know-what-we-don-t/main.jpg","alt":"mRNA Cancer Vaccines: What We Know, What We Don't"},"subtitle":"Nove studije donose nade, ali razlika između ‘obećavajućeg’ i ‘dokazanog’ ostaje ključna","subtitleEn":"Evidence Level: Research Stage — Not Clinical Reality","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/mrna-cancer-vaccines-what-we-know-what-we-don-t/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Evidence Level: Research Stage — Not Clinical Reality"},"tags":["mRNA vaccines","oncology","cancer treatment"],"geo":{"name":"Global","lat":0,"lon":0,"countryCode":"XX"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$13","part1En":"$14","part2En":"$15"},{"id":"2026-03-23-exercise-may-rewire-brains-scarred-by-childhood-tr","dbId":613,"title":"Exercise may rewire brains scarred by childhood trauma","titleEn":"Exercise may rewire brains scarred by childhood trauma","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"For decades, the prevailing assumption in neuroscience held that childhood trauma leaves indelible marks on the brain.","execSummary":"This study shifts the narrative from 'permanent damage' to 'modifiable resilience' in trauma-affected brains, but its observational nature means no direct clinical application yet. The key tension lies between promising neuroplasticity signals and the lack of actionable protocols—highlighting what’s possible, not what’s proven.","keyPoints":["Physical activity reshapes neural connectivity post-trauma","Study challenges ‘permanent damage’ narrative in neuroscience","No direct patient guidelines yet—research remains observational"],"source":{"name":"MedicalXpress","url":"https://medicalxpress.com/news/2026-03-physical-reshapes-neural-brain-resilient.html"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/exercise-may-rewire-brains-scarred-by-childhood-tr/main.jpg","alt":"Exercise may rewire brains scarred by childhood trauma"},"subtitle":"Nove spoznaje o neuroplastičnosti: koliko je mozak promjenjiv?","subtitleEn":"What the brain scans show—and what they don’t","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/exercise-may-rewire-brains-scarred-by-childhood-tr/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What the brain scans show—and what they don’t"},"tags":["Neuroplasticity","Childhood Trauma","Brain Development"],"geo":{"name":"Global","lat":0,"lon":0,"countryCode":"XX"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$16","part1En":"$17","part2En":"$18"},{"id":"2026-03-23-how-neuron-groups-shape-memorywhat-we-know","dbId":610,"title":"How neuron groups shape memory—what we know","titleEn":"How neuron groups shape memory—what we know","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"For over a century, neuroscientists have pursued a fundamental question: How does the human brain encode and store memories.","execSummary":"This article dissects the confirmed role of neuronal ensembles (engrams) in memory formation, emphasizing the gap between lab findings and clinical relevance. It critically assesses study limitations (sample sizes, animal models) and clarifies why this research doesn’t yet translate to patient care, while outlining its long-term potential for disorders like PTSD or Alzheimer’s.","keyPoints":["Engrams link neuron groups to memory","Evidence grade: early observational study","Limited clinical relevance for patients today"],"source":{"name":"MedicalXpress","url":"https://medicalxpress.com/news/2026-03-groups-neurons-formation-memories.html"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/how-neuron-groups-shape-memorywhat-we-know/main.jpg","alt":"How neuron groups shape memory—what we know"},"subtitle":"Što studije stvarno pokazuju – i što još uvijek ne razumijemo","subtitleEn":"What the evidence actually shows—and what it doesn’t","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/how-neuron-groups-shape-memorywhat-we-know/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What the evidence actually shows—and what it doesn’t"},"tags":["Neuroplasticity","Memory Formation","Neural Networks"],"geo":{"name":"Global","lat":0,"lon":0,"countryCode":"XX"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$19","part1En":"$1a","part2En":"$1b"},{"id":"2026-03-23-roche-s-breast-cancer-pill-fails-key-first-line-tr","dbId":605,"title":"Roche's Breast Cancer Pill Fails Key First-Line Trial","titleEn":"Roche's Breast Cancer Pill Fails Key First-Line Trial","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-23T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"Roche's breast cancer pill, persevERA, has failed in what [Endpoints News](https://endpts.","execSummary":"Roche’s breast cancer drug persevERA failed its pivotal Phase 3 trial, raising questions about its future and the gaps between early promise and clinical proof. This analysis dissects what the trial actually showed (and didn’t), the regulatory implications, and why this matters for precision oncology—without overstating the impact on current patient care.","keyPoints":["Phase 3 first-line treatment trial fails","PersevERA was potential blockbuster candidate","Trial details remain undisclosed"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/roche-s-breast-cancer-pill-fails-key-first-line-tr/main.jpg","alt":"Roche's Breast Cancer Pill Fails Key First-Line Trial"},"subtitle":"Rezultati faze 3: što studija stvarno pokazuje i što ostaje nejasno","subtitleEn":"What we know — and what we don't","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/roche-s-breast-cancer-pill-fails-key-first-line-tr/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What we know — and what we don't"},"tags":["Roche","Breast Cancer","Clinical Trial","Oncology"],"geo":{"name":"Basel, Switzerland","lat":47.5596,"lon":7.5886,"countryCode":"XX"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$1c","part1En":"Roche's breast cancer pill, persevERA, has failed in what [Endpoints News](https://endpts.com) describes as its most important Phase 3 trial — a first-line treatment study that the company had pinned considerable hopes on. According to available information, the drug had the potential to become Roche's biggest-ever selling medication, making this failure particularly significant for the pharmaceutical giant's oncology portfolio.\nThe trial focused on first-line treatment for breast cancer patients, representing a critical regulatory and commercial milestone. Phase 3 trials are the final stage before regulatory approval, designed to definitively demonstrate efficacy and safety in large patient populations.\nWhat we know is clear: the trial did not meet its primary endpoints. What we don't know is equally important — the specific details of the results, including whether any subgroups showed benefit, what the safety profile revealed, or whether Roche will pursue other indications.","part2En":"$1d"},{"id":"2026-03-22-antibiotic-resistant-gbs-strains-may-explain-newbo","dbId":600,"title":"Antibiotic-resistant GBS strains may explain newborn infections","titleEn":"Antibiotic-resistant GBS strains may explain newborn infections","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-22T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-22T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"Every year, [Group B Streptococcus (GBS)](https://www.","execSummary":"The study identifies mutant GBS strains resistant to standard antibiotics, explaining persistent neonatal infections despite prophylaxis. While the findings highlight a gap in current protocols, they don’t change clinical practice yet—emphasizing the need for surveillance over alarm. The angle focuses on the tension between evolving bacterial threats and static prevention strategies.","keyPoints":["Mutant GBS strains evade antibiotic treatment in birth canal","Link to pneumonia, meningitis, sepsis in newborns confirmed","No immediate change in clinical guidelines for pregnant women"],"source":{"name":"MedicalXpress","url":"https://medicalxpress.com/news/2026-03-mutant-group-strep-strains-infections.html"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/antibiotic-resistant-gbs-strains-may-explain-newbo/main.jpg","alt":"Antibiotic-resistant GBS strains may explain newborn infections"},"subtitle":"Novo istraživanje pokazuje kako evolucija bakterija izaziva nove rizike — ali što to znači za majke i bebe danas?","subtitleEn":"Why some babies still get infected—despite standard prevention","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/antibiotic-resistant-gbs-strains-may-explain-newbo/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Why some babies still get infected—despite standard prevention"},"tags":["Group B Strep","Antibiotic Resistance","Neonatal Infection"],"geo":{"name":"East Lansing, United States","lat":42.7369,"lon":-84.4839,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$1e","part1En":"$1f","part2En":"$20"},{"id":"2026-03-22-how-cholesterol-fuels-prostate-cancerand-why-it-ma","dbId":594,"title":"How cholesterol fuels prostate cancer—and why it matters","titleEn":"How cholesterol fuels prostate cancer—and why it matters","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-22T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-22T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"Prostate cancer’s ability to evade treatment has long puzzled oncologists.","execSummary":"The study identifies FGFR1 as a key regulator of cholesterol uptake in prostate cancer cells, potentially explaining tumor progression and treatment resistance. However, the research remains preclinical—no patient impact yet. The angle focuses on separating confirmed lab findings from speculative clinical implications, emphasizing methodology limits and the long road to therapeutic relevance.","keyPoints":["FGFR1 protein drives cholesterol uptake in tumors","Study links lipid metabolism to treatment resistance","No immediate patient impact, but research opens new questions"],"source":{"name":"MedicalXpress","url":"https://medicalxpress.com/news/2026-03-fgfr1-boosts-cholesterol-uptake-prostate.html"},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/how-cholesterol-fuels-prostate-cancerand-why-it-ma/main.jpg","alt":"How cholesterol fuels prostate cancer—and why it matters"},"subtitle":"Što studija s Teksaškog sveučilišta stvarno pokazuje — i što ostaje nejasno","subtitleEn":"A molecular clue in prostate cancer progression—what the lab shows and what it doesn’t","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/how-cholesterol-fuels-prostate-cancerand-why-it-ma/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A molecular clue in prostate cancer progression—what the lab shows and what it doesn’t"},"tags":["Prostate Cancer","FGFR1","Cancer Research"],"geo":{"name":"College Station, United States","lat":30.627977,"lon":-96.334407,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$21","part1En":"$22","part2En":"$23"},{"id":"2026-03-22-blood-marker-shows-promise-predicting-post-arrest-","dbId":590,"title":"Blood Marker Shows Promise Predicting Post-Arrest Cognition","titleEn":"Blood Marker Shows Promise Predicting Post-Arrest Cognition","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-22T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-22T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"For survivors of out-of-hospital cardiac arrest, one of the most difficult questions has long been: will cognitive function return.","execSummary":"A 2026 study presented at ESC Acute CardioVascular Care suggests that early measurement of neurofilament light chain (NfL) may improve prediction of cognitive impairment after out-of-hospital cardiac arrest. This analysis examines the evidence level (observational study), clinical relevance (none yet for patients), and critical gaps—including unknown sample size and methodology—while framing the finding as a research-stage signal rather than a practice-changing breakthrough.","keyPoints":["Study presented at ESC 2026 congress","Neurofilament light chain linked to cognitive outcomes","Research stage, not yet clinical practice"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/blood-marker-shows-promise-predicting-post-arrest-/main.jpg","alt":"Blood Marker Shows Promise Predicting Post-Arrest Cognition"},"subtitle":"Što stvarno pokazuje nova studija o predviđanju kognitivnih oštećenja – i što još ne znamo","subtitleEn":"What the evidence shows — and what it doesn't","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/blood-marker-shows-promise-predicting-post-arrest-/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What the evidence shows — and what it doesn't"},"tags":["Cardiac Arrest","Cognitive Impairment","Biomarker"],"geo":{"name":"Sophia Antipolis, France","lat":43.6053,"lon":7.0498,"countryCode":"FR"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$24","part1En":"For survivors of out-of-hospital cardiac arrest, one of the most difficult questions has long been: will cognitive function return? A study presented this week at [ESC Acute CardioVascular Care 2026](https://medicalxpress.com) suggests a possible answer may lie in a simple blood test. Researchers found that early measurement of neurofilament light chain (NfL) — a protein released when nerve cells are damaged — could help predict which patients are at higher risk of cognitive impairment following cardiac arrest.\nThe findings, presented at the annual congress of the [Association for Acute CardioVascular Care](https://www.escardio.org), represent an observational study. This is critical context: the research identifies a correlation, not yet a proven clinical tool. Sample size and methodology details remain to be fully scrutinized through peer review. What we have is a promising signal — but the distance between a conference presentation and validated clinical protocol is substantial.","part2En":"What does this mean for patients today? In practical terms, not much has changed yet. NfL measurement is not currently part of standard post-arrest care, and clinicians cannot act on these findings until they're validated through larger trials and regulatory review.\nWhat we don't know remains significant. We don't yet understand how NfL levels interact with other factors — age, arrest duration, intervention timing. We don't know whether early identification of cognitive risk would change patient outcomes, or simply provide information. And we don't have regulatory clearance for this specific application of NfL testing. According to [MedicalXpress](https://medicalxpress.com), the study positions NfL as a novel marker — but novelty and clinical utility are different measures.\nThe study marks a step forward in understanding brain injury after cardiac arrest. But the real measure isn't in laboratory values — it will be in whether this knowledge eventually improves care for the patients who need it most."},{"id":"2026-03-22-ai-finds-no-brain-structure-link-to-navigation-ski","dbId":582,"title":"AI finds no brain structure link to navigation skills—so what does?","titleEn":"AI finds no brain structure link to navigation skills—so what does?","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-22T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-22T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"For years, the idea that elite navigators—like London’s black-cab drivers—might have uniquely structured brains felt almost intuitive.","execSummary":"A University of Texas study using AI found no clear link between brain structure and navigation skills in young adults, challenging decades of assumptions—including famous London taxi driver research. The finding underscores the complexity of spatial cognition but offers no immediate clinical impact, instead pointing to gaps in how we measure brain-function relationships.","keyPoints":["AI analysis debunks brain structure-navigation link in young adults","London taxi driver studies challenged by new findings","Study limits: small sample, no causal claims"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/ai-finds-no-brain-structure-link-to-navigation-ski/main.jpg","alt":"AI finds no brain structure link to navigation skills—so what does?"},"subtitle":"Što studija Stevena Weisberga stvarno pokazuje — i što ne","subtitleEn":"A decades-old assumption falters—but what does this mean for neuroscience?","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/ai-finds-no-brain-structure-link-to-navigation-ski/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A decades-old assumption falters—but what does this mean for neuroscience?"},"tags":["Brain Navigation","Neuroscience","Steven Weisberg Study"],"geo":{"name":"Austin, Texas, United States","lat":30.2672,"lon":-97.7431,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$25","part1En":"$26","part2En":"$27"},{"id":"2026-03-20-new-dopamine-signal-found-in-mouse-brain-study","dbId":542,"title":"New Dopamine Signal Found in Mouse Brain Study","titleEn":"New Dopamine Signal Found in Mouse Brain Study","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-20T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-20T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"A Boston University-led research team has identified a previously unknown dopamine signal in the brain that appears to help determine whether movement is directed toward or away from a goal.","execSummary":"This study identifies a dopamine signal linked to goal-directed movement in mice, offering insights into how the brain processes visual cues—but its relevance to human medicine remains speculative. The angle focuses on separating confirmed findings from overreach, emphasizing study limits (animal model, controlled settings) and the absence of clinical applications today.","keyPoints":["Boston University team identifies new dopamine signal","Study published in Nature examined mouse behavior","Clinical applications remain years away"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/new-dopamine-signal-found-in-mouse-brain-study/main.jpg","alt":"New Dopamine Signal Found in Mouse Brain Study"},"subtitle":"Što studija stvarno pokazuje – i što još uvijek ne znamo","subtitleEn":"What the evidence shows — and what it doesn't","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/new-dopamine-signal-found-in-mouse-brain-study/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What the evidence shows — and what it doesn't"},"tags":["Dopamine Signaling","Neuroscience","Brain Function"],"geo":{"name":"Boston, United States","lat":42.3601,"lon":-71.0589,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$28","part1En":"$29","part2En":"$2a"},{"id":"2026-03-19-in-vivo-car-t-cell-breakthroughbut-how-far-from-pa","dbId":506,"title":"In-Vivo CAR T Cell Breakthrough—But How Far From Patients?","titleEn":"In-Vivo CAR T Cell Breakthrough—But How Far From Patients?","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-19T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-19T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"For patients with aggressive blood cancers, CAR T-cell therapy has been a lifeline—but its reliance on extracting, engineering, and reinfusing a patient’s own immune cells creates logistical hurdles.","execSummary":"This article dissects a new two-vector system for in vivo CAR-T cell generation, framing its preclinical success (leukemia, myeloma, solid tumor) against the reality of clinical translation. The angle focuses on the gap between promising lab results and patient impact, emphasizing regulatory hurdles, scalability questions, and the 10+ year timeline typical for such therapies.","keyPoints":["Two-vector system generates CAR T cells inside the body","Preclinical success against leukemia, myeloma, and solid tumors","No human trials yet—evidence grade remains early-stage"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/in-vivo-car-t-cell-breakthroughbut-how-far-from-pa/main.jpg","alt":"In-Vivo CAR T Cell Breakthrough—But How Far From Patients?"},"subtitle":"Što studija stvarno pokazuje – i što još moramo saznati","subtitleEn":"A step forward in cell therapy—if the lab translates to the clinic.","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/in-vivo-car-t-cell-breakthroughbut-how-far-from-pa/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A step forward in cell therapy—if the lab translates to the clinic."},"tags":["CAR-T cells","gene therapy","immunotherapy"],"geo":{"name":"Global","lat":0,"lon":0,"countryCode":"XX"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$2b","part1En":"$2c","part2En":"$2d"},{"id":"2026-03-17-a-new-tool-for-secretory-antibodiesbut-will-it-sca","dbId":445,"title":"A New Tool for Secretory Antibodies—But Will It Scale?","titleEn":"A New Tool for Secretory Antibodies—But Will It Scale?","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"Secretory immunoglobulin A (sIgA) has long been a tantalizing target for mucosal therapies—from gut disorders to respiratory infections—yet its instability and purification challenges have stymied large-scale production.","execSummary":"Austrian researchers developed a chromatography method for secretory IgA purification, targeting large-scale therapy production—but the study remains preclinical with no patient data. This analysis dissects the gap between lab promise and clinical reality, emphasizing unresolved questions about scalability, cost, and regulatory hurdles that determine whether this will ever reach patients.","keyPoints":["Austrian team refines purification for secretory IgA","Large-scale therapy production remains unproven","No resin name or clinical pipeline details released"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/a-new-tool-for-secretory-antibodiesbut-will-it-sca/main.jpg","alt":"A New Tool for Secretory Antibodies—But Will It Scale?"},"subtitle":"Korak naprijed u laboratoriju – ali koliko je blizu bolesničkog kreveta?","subtitleEn":"A method for purifying secretory IgA emerges—yet key questions linger before patient impact","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/a-new-tool-for-secretory-antibodiesbut-will-it-sca/subtitle.jpg","alt":"A method for purifying secretory IgA emerges—yet key questions linger before patient impact"},"tags":["Chromatography","Antibody Purification","Laboratory Research","Biomedical Engineering"],"geo":{"name":"Austria","lat":47.6966,"lon":13.3467,"countryCode":"XX"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$2e","part1En":"$2f","part2En":"$30"},{"id":"2026-03-17-measuring-beta-cells-a-step-toward-better-type-1-d","dbId":427,"title":"Measuring beta cells: A step toward better type 1 diabetes care?","titleEn":"Measuring beta cells: A step toward better type 1 diabetes care?","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-17T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"Type 1 diabetes remains a puzzle with a missing piece: how to stop—or reverse—the immune system’s relentless attack on insulin-producing beta cells.","execSummary":"Quantitative imaging of pancreatic beta cells offers a potential breakthrough in tracking type 1 diabetes progression, but remains in early research stages with no immediate clinical application. The article dissects the evidence level, methodological limits, and why this matters more for future therapy development than current patient care — while stressing the gap between technical feasibility and proven utility.","keyPoints":["Beta cell loss drives type 1 diabetes progression","Imaging beta cell mass may guide future treatments","No clinical impact yet—early-stage research only"],"source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/measuring-beta-cells-a-step-toward-better-type-1-d/main.jpg","alt":"Measuring beta cells: A step toward better type 1 diabetes care?"},"subtitle":"Što nova tehnika snimanja stvarno donosi — i što još uvijek ne znamo","subtitleEn":"What the science actually shows—and what it doesn’t","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/measuring-beta-cells-a-step-toward-better-type-1-d/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What the science actually shows—and what it doesn’t"},"tags":["Type 1 Diabetes","Beta Cell Imaging","Diabetes Research"],"geo":{"name":"Global","lat":0,"lon":0,"countryCode":"XX"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$31","part1En":"$32","part2En":"$33"},{"id":"2026-03-16-cancers-hidden-editor-a-new-way-to-measure-gene-sp","dbId":426,"title":"Cancer’s Hidden Editor: A New Way to Measure Gene Splicing","titleEn":"Cancer’s Hidden Editor: A New Way to Measure Gene Splicing","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"Cancer has long been understood as a disease of faulty genes, but its deeper mechanics lie in how those genes are *edited*—not just mutated.","execSummary":"A new tool directly measures how cancer cells rewrite genetic instructions via splicing, offering unprecedented insight into tumor behavior—but remains far from clinical application. The study confirms tumors systematically alter protein production to survive, yet its immediate relevance for patients is zero; the focus is on understanding mechanisms, not therapy. Key tension: the gap between molecular discovery and treatable target.","source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/cancers-hidden-editor-a-new-way-to-measure-gene-sp/main.jpg","alt":"Cancer’s Hidden Editor: A New Way to Measure Gene Splicing"},"subtitle":"Što studija stvarno pokazuje – i što još uvijek ne znamo o ovom procesu","subtitleEn":"What the study actually reveals—and what it doesn’t","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/cancers-hidden-editor-a-new-way-to-measure-gene-sp/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What the study actually reveals—and what it doesn’t"},"tags":["Cancer","Genetic Regulation","Oncology"],"geo":{"name":"Menlo Park, CA","lat":37.4529,"lon":-122.1817,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$34","part1En":"$35","part2En":"$36"},{"id":"2026-03-16-gastric-cancer-s-three-paths-what-new-evidence-rev","dbId":384,"title":"Gastric Cancer's Three Paths: What New Evidence Reveals","titleEn":"Gastric Cancer's Three Paths: What New Evidence Reveals","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"A new study published in the journal Gut [https://gut.","execSummary":"This study in *Gut* identifies three distinct biological pathways for gastric cancer beyond *H. pylori*, offering potential for precision medicine but no immediate clinical changes. The angle focuses on separating confirmed findings (pathway existence, prognostic links) from speculative implications (new treatments, prevention strategies), while emphasizing methodology limits and the observational nature of the research.","source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/gastric-cancer-s-three-paths-what-new-evidence-rev/main.jpg","alt":"Gastric Cancer's Three Paths: What New Evidence Reveals"},"subtitle":"Što studija stvarno pokazuje – i što još uvijek ne znamo","subtitleEn":"Complex interactions shape distinct tumor routes, but clinical application remains distant","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/gastric-cancer-s-three-paths-what-new-evidence-rev/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Complex interactions shape distinct tumor routes, but clinical application remains distant"},"tags":["future-pulse","automated","medicine"],"geo":{"name":"San Francisco, US","lat":37.7749,"lon":-122.4194,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$37","part1En":"$38","part2En":"$39"},{"id":"2026-03-16-co2-is-rising-in-our-blood-scientists-aren-t-sure-","dbId":365,"title":"CO₂ Is Rising in Our Blood. Scientists Aren't Sure What It Means.","titleEn":"CO₂ Is Rising in Our Blood. Scientists Aren't Sure What It Means.","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"For roughly 300,000 years, human bodies evolved in an atmosphere containing 200 to 300 parts per million of carbon dioxide.","execSummary":"This article examines the confirmed rise of CO₂ levels in human blood—now above 420ppm, higher than ever in human history—but focuses on what we *don’t* know: the clinical relevance. It dissects the gap between observational data and causal proof, emphasizing the need for targeted research while avoiding alarmism.","source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/co2-is-rising-in-our-blood-scientists-aren-t-sure-/main.jpg","alt":"CO₂ Is Rising in Our Blood. Scientists Aren't Sure What It Means."},"subtitle":"Razina ugljičnog dioksida nikad nije bila viša – ali što to stvarno znači za naše tijelo?","subtitleEn":"What the Evidence Shows — And What It Doesn't","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/co2-is-rising-in-our-blood-scientists-aren-t-sure-/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What the Evidence Shows — And What It Doesn't"},"tags":["future-pulse","automated","medicine"],"geo":{"name":"Menlo Park, CA","lat":37.4529,"lon":-122.1817,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$3a","part1En":"$3b","part2En":"$3c"},{"id":"2026-03-16-smart-underwear-study-suggests-higher-daily-gas-co","dbId":361,"title":"Smart Underwear Study Suggests Higher Daily Gas Counts","titleEn":"Smart Underwear Study Suggests Higher Daily Gas Counts","category":"medicine","date":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","scrapeDateDate":"2026-03-16T12:00:00Z","excerpt":"A new wearable device designed to measure flatulence has produced an unexpected preliminary finding: humans may pass gas significantly more often than previously believed.","execSummary":"A groundbreaking study using 'smart underwear' reveals that people may pass gas up to 32 times a day—far more than previously estimated. While the findings offer new insights into gut microbial activity, the study's small sample size and methodological limitations mean that these results are preliminary. This research could pave the way for better understanding gut health, but clinical applications remain distant.","source":{"name":"","url":""},"image":{"url":"/images/articles/smart-underwear-study-suggests-higher-daily-gas-co/main.jpg","alt":"Smart Underwear Study Suggests Higher Daily Gas Counts"},"subtitle":"Što studija stvarno pokazuje o crijevnoj mikrobioti i svakodnevnim plinovima","subtitleEn":"What the evidence actually shows about gut microbial tracking","subtitleImage":{"url":"/images/articles/smart-underwear-study-suggests-higher-daily-gas-co/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What the evidence actually shows about gut microbial tracking"},"tags":["future-pulse","automated","medicine"],"geo":{"name":"California, United States","lat":36.7783,"lon":-119.4179,"countryCode":"US"},"featured":false,"approved":true,"content":"$3d","part1En":"A new wearable device designed to measure flatulence has produced an unexpected preliminary finding: humans may pass gas significantly more often than previously believed. Researchers developed \"smart underwear\" equipped with sensors capable of detecting hydrogen produced by gut microbes, offering a non-invasive method to track gastrointestinal activity in real-world settings. Early data from this technology suggests an average frequency of 32 episodes per day, a figure that substantially exceeds historical medical estimates. While the headline number grabs attention, the true significance lies in the methodology's potential to transform how we understand gut health outside the laboratory. For decades, data on human flatulence relied on self-reporting or short-term clinical observations, both of which are prone to significant error. This [wearable approach](https://www.sciencedaily.com) attempts to capture continuous, objective data, bridging the gap between controlled studies and daily life.","part2En":"However, interpreting these findings requires strict adherence to evidence grading. This remains an early-stage observational study, and the sample size limits the ability to generalize results to the global population immediately. The device functions as a research tool rather than a diagnostic product, with no current regulatory approval for clinical use. The upcoming \"Human Flatus Atlas\" aims to map normal patterns of gas production, but until larger, peer-reviewed trials are completed, the figure of 32 times daily should be viewed as a promising signal rather than a definitive medical fact. For patients today, this technology does not change clinical guidelines or suggest new treatments for gastrointestinal distress. It represents a step forward in data collection precision, yet the clinical relevance remains confined to the research sphere. The distinction between a novel measurement technique and a proven therapeutic insight is critical here."}]}]]}],["$L3e"],"$L3f"]}],"loading":null,"isPartial":false}
